pull.title: Remove unused Python imports
pull.body: The commit in this PR removes unused Python imports.

events.body: Makes sense. Is there an automated tool you used to find these?

@laanwj Yes, [`pycodestyle`](https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pycodestyle) (formerly `pep8`) is probably the most common tool for checking Python code against the Python Software Foundation's [Style Guide for Python Code (PEP-8)](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/). Unused imports is one class of violations covered by `pycodestyle`.

I've done some cleanup work for the `apple/swift` project - [see here](https://github.com/apple/swift/pulls?utf8=%E2%9C%93&q=is%3Apr%20author%3Apracticalswift%20is%3Amerged) - which included things such as bringing the Python code base in line with PEP-8. Please let me know if that kind of contributions would be welcome in the Bitcoin project and I'll dig in! :-)

ACK

Feel free to open PRs for tidying up python coding style. I'm happy to review anything in the qa directory.
@jnewbery Do you know who to ask for a review of PR #9529? :-)

@jnewbery What is the proper protocol to follow w.r.t. to submitting Python cleanups? Should I wait for this initial Python cleanup PR to get merged before proceeding with further cleanups, or what is the preferred way to proceed? :-)

@practicalswift - probably best to ask @MarcoFalke since he maintains the qa and test code. In general I'd recommend not making parallel PRs which touch a lot of files, since you'll probably end up having to rebase.
@jnewbery Makes sense! My second Python cleanup PR is #9532 which removes 8 unused Python variables (+ one unused variable in the C++ code :-)).

I think it makes sense to clean up the python code base in qa/ but
please make sure you are not "exceeding the goal". We already had
cleanup pulls which changed to a max line length to 80 chars among
other things. It turned out the patch was impossible to review,
actually changed behavior and would have introduced bugs. I'd rather
have "ugly" code that works than some PEP8 code that crashes.

Just ask yourself if a specific cleanup task is worth it and easy to
review, then it should be fine.

issue.title: Bug fix: Update the instance variable self.lastDate (not the locally scoped variable lastDate)
Fix invalid checks (NULL checks after dereference, redundant checks, etc.)
issue.body:
Contains:
* Remove redundant `NULL` checks after throwing `new`
* Remove redundant check (`!ecc` is always true)
* Remove duplicate `uriParts.size() > 0` check
* Use two boolean literals instead of re-using variable
